This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it deals with deep generative models such as VAE and GAN, which are commonly used in machine learning. It also discusses the development of new techniques for maximum likelihood inference in latent space, which is a key aspect of machine learning. 

The paper also involves the use of techniques from computer vision (cs.CV) as it deals with the representation of data in a lower dimensional space. 

The use of neural networks in approximating the Riemannian metric and cometric tensor suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

The paper's focus on statistical techniques suggests that it may also belong to the category of cs.IT (Information Theory). 

Finally, the paper's use of nonlinear manifold statistics suggests that it may also belong to the category of cs.ST (Statistics).
